         <!--put exact source text here in new <p></p> tags for each paragraph e.g. <p>Mr Parnell addresed the crowd [etc]</p>-->
         <p>Mr. C. S. Parnell supported the resolution. The Irish political prisoners, he said, had drawn the sword not to strike against the liberties of Englishmen, but to defend the liberties of Ireland (cheers), to protest against a system by which the better classes of their people were being debauched and demoralised. They rise against a system of government which would have debauched and demoralised any people on the face of the earth except the Irish people (cheers). Many of them had given up lucrative positions for the cause in which they were engaged. He contended that the Fenian prisoners had done a moral wrong, and quoted a speech of Mr. Wendell Phillips, who declared that England ruled Ireland by a policy of extermination, and appealed to the grand jury of the American nation to give a verdict against her (cheers).</p>
